  "text": "We have shown through numerical integration that, unless the mean flow is barotropically unStable, equatorial Rossby waves decay algebraically with time in a shear flow, just like their midlatitude counterparts. Initial conditions in the form of Hermite functions, which describe the usual Rossby modes on a resting mean state, have a broad spectrum in latitudinal wavenumber. Because some wavenumbers m are decaying while others are growing, our numerical solutions show no signs of the transient growth phase discussed in [CITATION_1] . We have explained why this is true of both midlatitude and equatorial Rossby waves. In either case, the energy of the wave disturbance will grow a noticeable amount only when the initial condition has a Fourier spectrum in latitudinal wavenumber m which is sharply peaked about some wavenumber m = m 0 such that m 0 >> k where k is the zonal wavenumber of the disturbance, and where the sign of m 0 is such that the waves are tilted against the mean flow.",
